---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
import ProjectCard from '../components/ProjectCard.astro';

const FITSCRIPT_URL = 'https://fitscript.emilydenis.com';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Emily Denis | Product Manager"
  description="Product manager who loves solving customer problems end to end. Case studies from three consumer apps I built and shipped: an AI training coach, a social planning tool, and a baby nap scheduler."
>
  <Header />

  <!-- Hero -->
  <section class="mx-auto max-w-5xl px-6 pb-20 pt-20 sm:pt-28">
    <p class="text-sm font-bold uppercase tracking-wide text-indigo-600 dark:text-indigo-400">
      Product manager
    </p>
    <h1 class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-4xl font-extrabold leading-[1.1] tracking-tight text-zinc-900 dark:text-white sm:text-6xl">
      I love solving customer problems end to end.
    </h1>
    <p class="mt-6 max-w-2xl text-lg leading-relaxed text-zinc-600 dark:text-zinc-400">
      I'm Emily. My favorite part of product work is staying close to one
      problem from the first conversation to the shipped fix. I've built three
      small consumer apps that way: FitScript, an AI training coach; HangEasy,
      a tool for making plans with friends; and NapMap, a nap scheduler for
      tired parents. Each one started as a real problem in my own life, and
      all three are live and in use today.
    </p>
    <div class="mt-8 flex flex-wrap items-center gap-3">
      <a href="#work" class="btn-primary">See the work</a>
      <a href={`${FITSCRIPT_URL}/demo`} target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="btn-secondary">
        Try the FitScript demo ↗
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Work -->
  <section id="work" class="border-t border-zinc-950/5 bg-white py-20 dark:border-white/5 dark:bg-zinc-900/40">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-5xl px-6">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-zinc-900 dark:text-white">Work</h2>
      <p class="mt-3 max-w-2xl text-zinc-600 dark:text-zinc-400">
        Each case study walks through the problem, the decisions I made along
        the way, and how I judge whether it's working. All three link to the
        live product so you can try it yourself.
      </p>

      <div class="mt-10 grid grid-cols-1 gap-8">
        <ProjectCard
          title="FitScript"
          tagline="An AI coach that fits training to real life"
          description="FitScript reads your sleep, recovery, and race calendar, asks how you're actually feeling, and suggests one workout for the day with the reasoning spelled out in your own numbers. You can adjust the plan just by telling the coach what's going on. Every change to the coach has to pass an eval suite before it ships, and a rules engine steps in whenever the AI is unavailable."
          image="/images/fitscript-dashboard.png"
          imageAlt="FitScript dashboard showing an AI-coached workout recommendation with reasoning"
          href="/fitscript"
          chips={['Personalized guidance', 'Conversational coaching', 'Evals', 'Oura + Strava + Apple Health', 'Claude']}
          links={[
            { label: 'Live demo', href: `${FITSCRIPT_URL}/demo` },
            { label: 'App', href: FITSCRIPT_URL },
          ]}
        />

        <div class="grid grid-cols-1 gap-8 md:grid-cols-2">
          <ProjectCard
            title="HangEasy"
            tagline="Make plans that actually happen"
            description="Group threads fizzle and another month goes by. HangEasy gives the organizer a two minute flow and lets guests RSVP in one tap, with no app and no account. The whole product exists to get a plan from 'we should hang' to a confirmed date."
            image="/images/hangeasy-hero.png"
            imageAlt="HangEasy landing page with a Pizza Night hang card and live RSVPs"
            href="/hangeasy"
            accent="text-fuchsia-600 dark:text-fuchsia-400"
            chips={['Social planning', 'One-tap RSVP', 'SMS', 'Web app']}
            links={[{ label: 'hangeasy.app', href: 'https://hangeasy.app' }]}
          />

          <ProjectCard
            title="NapMap"
            tagline="Nap schedules without the math"
            description="Log a nap as it happens and the rest of the baby's day recalculates, using wake windows that adjust to your baby's age and actual rhythm. I built it for my own daughter and kept it free on purpose. It currently holds a 5.0 rating on the App Store."
            image="/images/napmap-hero.png"
            imageAlt="NapMap landing page showing a baby's recalculated nap day"
            href="/napmap"
            accent="text-emerald-700 dark:text-emerald-400"
            chips={['iOS + PWA', 'Adaptive scheduling', 'Caregiver sharing', 'Free forever']}
            links={[
              { label: 'App Store', href: 'https://apps.apple.com/us/app/napmap-baby-nap-schedule/id6783008121' },
              { label: 'napmap.app', href: 'https://napmap.app' },
            ]}
          />
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- About / How I work -->
  <section id="about" class="py-20">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-5xl px-6">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-zinc-900 dark:text-white">How I work</h2>
      <div class="mt-10 grid grid-cols-1 gap-6 md:grid-cols-3">
        <div class="card p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-zinc-900 dark:text-white">Start with someone's real day</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-zinc-600 dark:text-zinc-400">
            Each of these apps came from watching a problem up close: a training
            plan that fell apart after a newborn's bad night, a group chat that
            never picked a date, wake-window math at 3am. I try to understand
            the whole problem before deciding what to build.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="card p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-zinc-900 dark:text-white">Hold AI to a measurable bar</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-zinc-600 dark:text-zinc-400">
            FitScript's coach only changes when its eval suite passes. Writing
            those scenarios taught me more about the product than any single
            feature did, and the suite caught a real safety gap before a user
            ever hit it.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="card p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-zinc-900 dark:text-white">Meet people where they are</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-zinc-600 dark:text-zinc-400">
            A rough night with a newborn is real training load. A guest who
            won't download an app is a design constraint. I'd rather adapt the
            product to the person than ask the person to adapt to the product.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p class="mt-10 max-w-2xl leading-relaxed text-zinc-600 dark:text-zinc-400">
        I'm an individual contributor and I like it that way: talking to users,
        deciding what to build, designing, writing the code, and fixing what
        breaks in production. If any of this resonates with what you're working
        on, I'd love to hear from you at
        <a href="mailto:emilydenis43@gmail.com" class="link">emilydenis43@gmail.com</a>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <Footer />
</BaseLayout>
